<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>WWC0030</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">WWC0030</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Becky Francis, Professor of Education and Social Justice, King’s College London.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Education is often seen as a driver of social mobility. Yet the evidence shows that in the UK, schooling at best replicates, and at worst exacerbates, existing inequality.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Moreover, as Lupton </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">et al </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2009), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clifton &amp; Cook </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2012) and others have shown</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issue is not just about poverty (FSM): s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tatistics highlight a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">diagonal gradient of achievement that correlates precisely with social class. Hence there is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">inequality for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children from ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">blue collar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ families</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">– and my own research has shown how</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> many of these are learning in lower quality schools (Francis, 2011). Hence I strongly welcome the Select Committee’s inquiry. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">My academic expertise is in the relationship between social identity (social class, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gender, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ethnicity) and educational achi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> social and education inequality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and education policy. My evidence is based on my broad knowledge of the research here; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> specifically from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some of my </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">recent work, including:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Francis, B. (2011). (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Un)Satisfactory? Enhancing Life Chances by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Improving 'Satisfactory' Schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. London: The RSA.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Francis, B. (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What the government can and should be doing to increase social mobility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Leicester: ASCL.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Francis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, B.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> &amp; Hutchings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, M. (forthcoming, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Parent Power? Using money and information to bo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ost children’s chances of educational success</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, London: Sutton Trust.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Francis, B. &amp; Wong, B. (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What is preventing social mobility? Literature Review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Leicester: ASCL.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Perry, E., and Francis, B. (2010). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The social class gap for educational achievement: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">a review of the literature.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">London: The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">RSA.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The factors responsible for white working class pupils’ educational underachievement, including the impact of home and family</span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clearly, educational inequality cannot be divorced from other aspects of social po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">licy: Family income, job prospects, health, housing, and social culture are all important. Poorer people have fewer resources – less time and energy, and knowledge, as well as less money – to devote to their children’s education. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Financial and social capit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">al are both important factors. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">My recent research with Hutchings for the Sutton Trust (Francis &amp; Hutchings, forthcoming) has amply demonstrated how lack of money and information constrains working class families’ ability to support their children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">education, and to employ the ‘choice’ strategies adopted by many of their middle class counterparts in accessing the best education.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Children from lower socio-economic groups tend to be behind on entry to early years: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">By the age of three, poor children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">have been assessed to be one year behind their affluent counterparts in terms of communication (National Equality Panel, 2010). And the EPPE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2004) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and EP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SE </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(2012) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work has demonstrated the importance of the home learning environment for children’s school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> readiness and development. However, crucially, the gap for attainment grows, rather than narrows, over schooling (DfE, cited in Francis 2013). There are several key explanations for this:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disadvantaged pupils are concentrated in poorer quality schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rancis, 2011)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disadvantaged pupils are under-represented in high-attaining schools (including grammar schools, and high achieving private and non-selective state schools)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Sutton Trust)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disadvantaged pupils are concentrated in lower streams and sets, which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> tend to be subject to poorer pedagogy</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disadvantaged pupils may be disengaged from schooling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(Perry &amp; Francis, 2010)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disadvantaged pupils are less likely to pursue subjects that enable progression routes to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">prestigious universities and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">high status careers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Richmond</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> &amp; Freedman 2009; Wolf, 2011; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Candy, 2013; Iann</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elli,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2013).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many of these factors are consequences of England’s highly socially segregated school system</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Our private school sector is significantly larger than that of most of our international c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">omparators, we maintain fully or partially-selective schools</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in many parts of the country, and research has shown processes of covert selection via admissions in faith schools, and indeed over-subscribed maintained schools (West et al, 2009). Middle-class</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> social and financial capital enables more advantaged parents to find ways to access the best schools. These tendencies are exacerbated by the ‘choice’ agenda, wherein some parents are better able to access the rules of the game, and have better purchasing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> power to realise ‘choice’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Exley, 2012</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; Francis &amp; Hutchings, forthcoming)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. England’s a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ccountability arrangements do not incentivise balanced intakes, as schools may view disadvantaged pupils as higher risk in terms of a school’s energies and its performance measures. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether the problem is significantly worse for white working class boys </span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">than girls</span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">White working class girls are underperforming compared to their male and female middle class counterparts, and as such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it is important that their needs are not overlooked. Nevertheless, Black and white working class boys are the lowest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> achievi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng groups (excepting for the smaller, but significantly lower achieving group of male and female traveller and gypsy Roma children). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is important to consider how different aspects of identity, such as gender, ethnicity and class, intersect in their im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pact on outcomes for different groups.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Much of the difference in performance according to gender, across all social groups, can be explained by girls’ out-performance of boys at language and literacy (Francis &amp; Skelton, 2005). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are also issues conc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">erning gender constructions, including an emphasis on ‘laddish’ constructions of identity and behaviour that elevate ‘having a laugh’, rebellion, and ‘laddish interests’ (sport, active heterosexuality etc) over diligence and obedience (Francis, 1999; 2000)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. It has been shown how these behaviours may impede boys’ academic application (and indeed can also impede that of their classmates). Moreover, these issues of identity couple with engagement: as Jackson (2004) shows, masculine competitiveness mean that bo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ys </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> especially uncomfortable with being seen to fail, or struggle</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. If they cannot ‘win’ academically they may instead invest in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">activities they can excel at, such as sport, or disruptive classroom behaviours.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What steps schools can take to improve</span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the educational outcomes and attainmen</span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">t of white working class pupils?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Levels of within-school segregation are very high in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> likely explanation is the prevalence of setting and streaming, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> working class pupils are over-represented in low set</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (Dunne et al, 2007)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. A series of poor practices are associated with low-tracked groups. S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chools need to reflect on their practices for setting and streaming, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and ensure that pupils in low sets are not being disadvantaged. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Schools also need to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure ef</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fective strategies are in place to address socio-economic gaps for attainment. For primary schools, ensuring that all pupils meet the required levels of literacy and numeracy by KS2 is vital. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One-to-one tuition or small group catch-up sessions are also imp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ortant post KS1 for those that have fallen behind here. E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vidence also emphasizes the importance of parental involvement. The pupil premium directly facilitates schools’ resourcing of strategies, but clearly these need to be based on research evidence (the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sutton Trust/Education Endowment Foundation Toolkit, and Oftsed accountability, are both making an important contribution here, though more could be done to support schools with exemplars of effective practice). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The import</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of high expectations from teachers cannot be over-emphasized. This also applies to the curriculum and exam entry: last year only 5% pupils on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">free school meals gained the ‘EB</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ac’ collection of GCSEs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (DfE, 2013)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The potential for a wider range of educat</span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ional approaches, for example vocational pathways, to improve outcomes for white working class pupils. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a real danger in assumptions that working class pupils (and parents) are more interested in vocational qualifications. Research with working </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">class parents shows that they have very high aspirations for their children (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Kintrea et al, 2011). Medicine and Law are vocational pathways, but they require a degree. As Wolf (2011) showed so effectively in her recent report, it is working class chil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dren that are being short-changed by qualifications that have little currency in the workplace. Models that facilitate different pathways between ‘vocational’ and ‘academic’ are, in the UK</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, inevitably characterized by social class, perpetuating inequaliti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es in future career, status and remuneration. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Iann</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s (2013) recent research examining longitudinal data clearly demonstrates the import of an academic curriculum for future outcomes. She found that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">middle class pupils were more likely to pursue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘traditional’ academic subjects (languages, English, maths and science) that were found to be highly valued in the labour market. She also found that “net of the effect of origin class and individual ability, all or most of the advantage associated with at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tendance at selective schools is accounted for by the curriculum studied there” (Ianelli, 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, p. 907). Hence curriculum studied is more significant than school type in future outcomes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As such, models with ‘separate paths’ are inherently problematic; bu</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t especially </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pre-16 when young people do not necessarily understand the consequences of their choices. The evidence is clear that all young people should be encouraged to maintain an academic curriculum for as long as possible. Nevertheless, the issue o</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f engagement should not be ignored: young people need to maintain motivation for study, and engagement with education. As such, their curricula must contain sufficient flex for students to </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pursue subjects for which they have a passion (arguably all student</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s should pursue at least one arts/skills-based subject). Hence it</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is arguable that the current EB</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ac might be slightly narrowed (e.g. to 5 or 6 subjects) to enable greater flexibility – but the expectation should be that all young people (or as many as poss</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ible) pursue this. </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We also need far better advice and guidance for young people approaching Key Stage 4 on their curriculum subject </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">choices and implications for the future</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; and </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">better, targeted careers education (especially important for young people from </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disadvantaged backgrounds)</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What role Government can play in delivering improved educational outcomes for white working class pupils. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0070c0; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">upil premium a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hugely important initiative. My recent role on the judging panel of the 2013 DfE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/TES Pupil Premium Awards gave me additional insight as to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">: many schools commented that they had not been aware of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">socio-economic attainment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gap at their school until the pupil premium was introduced. The Government’s willingness to listen t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o advice and develop policy accordingly has also aided efficacy: the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">increased accountability (via Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">transparency on spending</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">addressed concerns </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the money was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t reaching the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that generated it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; and supports </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">development of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">evid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ence-based practice. Likewise, the recent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> increased focus on primary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schooling is affirmed by the research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Some key </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">challenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s remain:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> money is insufficient  to achieve the desired improvement for disadvantaged pupils (Sibieta, 2009)</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the money is i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsufficient to incentivise the best schools to take additional FSM pupils, given the high-stakes nature of league tables and other performance indicators. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Quality of activities undertaken by schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All of these can be improved to some extent, though </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this may be circumscribed by a)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> amount available to spend, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">b) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">counter-incentives </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of performance indicators </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">new performance indicators may help, to some extent). But fundamentally, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the scale of challenge is also enormous: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the level</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of financial and social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capital inequality between families cannot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> simply be compensated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> alone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eed to address wealth inequality, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">empower and engage working class parents. </span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ith regard to the education system, however, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e need to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> address the current patchiness of quality, to ensure that every school is a good school. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">And fundamentally, we need more social mixing.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To secure school improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to reduce ‘patchy’ quality and resulting between-school segregation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Government need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> increase transparency and accountability within its academies programme, and take further steps to realise the promise of school-to-school collaboration set out in its 2010 White Paper. Arguably, this will require area-level oversight and brokerage.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e Government needs to:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Monitor the comparative performance of academy sponsors, act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to terminate funding agreements where necessary</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">educe the length of the Funding Agreement from 7 to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a maximum of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ears</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Support inception of the College of Teachers</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Hold converter academies to account for their commitments to support other schools</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Incentivise good teachers and middle leaders to teach in schools in more challenging circumstances, for example through awards and/or middle leadership development schemes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ducation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oards with a specific remit for strategic direction and the commissioning of support for improvement across a local area. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Additionally, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o ensure equality of access to high quality education, and increase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">social mixing,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the Government should:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Continue to improve the quality and qualifications of the early y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rs workforce, and take further steps to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">disadvantaged families access good quality provision</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Continue, and if possible extend the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resourcin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">g of the pupil premium</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Consider introduction of m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tested </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘education enrichment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vouchers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> for parents, to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">empower and engage working class parents in their children’s education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (beginning in the E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Find ways, via</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> progress and value-added measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, to incentivise and celebrate those schools that secure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">better than expected progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> among their pupils – and these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">performance indicators</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to be applied to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ontinue to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">private</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> schools to join the state sector via adoption of academy status, and to treat remaining private schools like other edu-businesses.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mprove the range</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> quality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and accessibility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">on local education provision </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">available to working class parents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and ensure high quality careers advice and guidance is available</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.36pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Address school admissions – specifically:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">End the practice of VA, foundation and academy schools being their own admissions authority, and convening their own appeals panels. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Direct schoo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ls to publish the data on who applied to their school, and who was granted admission, in relation to socio-economic background</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ffice of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">chools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">djudicator to scrutinise this data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Empower and resource the Office of the Schools Adjudicator </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to carry out random checks and enforcement of schools’ admissions procedures.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I hope this brief submission is helpful. Social-class inequality in educational achievement is a deeply embedded problem which may be connected to our (still) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">classed society and hierarchized education system. However, hope that I have outlined some key issues and potential ways forward. Again, I applaud the Committee’s attention to this important issue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Academies Commission (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Unleashing Greatness: Getting the best from an academised system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, London: RSA/Pearson Think Tank.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Candy, S. (2013) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(Un)Informed Choices?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> London: Pearson Think Tank.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Clifton, J. &amp; Cook, W. (2012) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A Long Division: Closing the attainment gap in England’s seco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ndary schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, London: IPPR.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span